items.abstract: <jats:p>Using a game-theoretic characterization of Baire spaces, conditions upon the domain and the range are given to ensure a fat set<mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="$C\left( f \right)$" id="E1"><mml:mi>C</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo>(</mml:mo><mml:mi>f</mml:mi><mml:mo>)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math>of points of continuity in the sets of type<mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="$X \times \left\{ y \right\}$" id="E2"><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>×</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mo>{</mml:mo><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo>}</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math>,<mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="$y \in Y$" id="E3"><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo>∈</mml:mo><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi></mml:math>for certain almost separately continuous functions<mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="$f:X \times Y \to Z$" id="E4"><mml:mi>f</mml:mi><mml:mo>:</mml:mo><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mo>×</mml:mo><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo>→</mml:mo><mml:mi>Z</mml:mi></mml:math>. These results (especially Theorem B) generalize Mibu's. First Theorem, previous theorems of the author, answers one of his problems as well as they are closely related to some other results of Debs [1] and Mibu [2].</jats:p>
